In Spring Boot and Java development, annotations are extremely important because they reduce boilerplate code and allow the framework to automatically configure components. For someone preparing to work with Spring Boot (like for backend or microservices roles), there are some annotations you must know. I’ll explain them with their significance so you understand why they are used.

Core Spring Boot Annotations

@SpringBootApplication

Significance
This is the main annotation used to start a Spring Boot application. It combines three annotations:

@Configuration

@EnableAutoConfiguration

@ComponentScan

Meaning
Spring Boot will automatically configure the project, scan components, and treat the class as a configuration class.

Example

@SpringBootApplication
public class DemoApplication {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(DemoApplication.class, args);
    }
}

Dependency Injection Annotations

@Autowired

Significance
Automatically injects the required dependency (object) into a class. This is the foundation of Spring’s Dependency Injection.

Example

@Autowired
UserService userService;

Meaning
Spring automatically creates the object and injects it.

@Component

Significance
Marks a class as a Spring-managed component. Spring automatically detects it during component scanning.

Example

@Component
public class EmailService {
}

@Service

Significance
Specialized version of @Component used for service layer classes.

Example

@Service
public class UserService {
}

Meaning
Indicates business logic layer.

@Repository

Significance
Used for database access layer (DAO). Also enables exception translation for database operations.

Example

@Repository
public class UserRepository {
}

@Controller

Significance
Used to define a web controller in Spring MVC.

Example

@Controller
public class HomeController {
}

@RestController

Significance
Combination of:

@Controller

@ResponseBody

It returns JSON directly instead of a view.

Example

@RestController
public class UserController {
}

Request Mapping Annotations

@RequestMapping

Significance
Maps HTTP requests to handler methods.

Example

@RequestMapping("/users")

@GetMapping

Significance
Handles HTTP GET requests.

Example

@GetMapping("/users")

@PostMapping

Significance
Handles HTTP POST requests.

Example

@PostMapping("/users")

@PutMapping

Significance
Handles HTTP PUT requests.

@DeleteMapping

Significance
Handles HTTP DELETE requests.

Request Data Handling Annotations

@PathVariable

Significance
Extracts values from URL.

Example

@GetMapping("/users/{id}")
public String getUser(@PathVariable int id) {
}

@RequestParam

Significance
Gets query parameters from URL.

Example

@GetMapping("/search")
public String search(@RequestParam String name) {
}

URL example
/search?name=John

@RequestBody

Significance
Converts JSON request body into a Java object.

Example

@PostMapping("/users")
public void addUser(@RequestBody User user) {
}

Configuration Annotations

@Configuration

Significance
Marks a class as a configuration class that defines beans.

@Bean

Significance
Used to create and register a bean manually.

Example

@Bean
public RestTemplate restTemplate() {
    return new RestTemplate();
}

Database Related Annotations (JPA)

@Entity

Significance
Marks a class as a database entity.

Example

@Entity
public class User {
}

@Id

Significance
Defines the primary key.

@GeneratedValue

Significance
Automatically generates the primary key.

Example

@Id
@GeneratedValue
private Long id;

@Table

Significance
Specifies database table name.

Example

@Table(name="users")

Other Useful Annotations

@ResponseBody

Significance
Returns data directly as JSON/XML instead of a view.

@Value

Significance
Injects values from application.properties.

Example

@Value("${server.port}")
private String port;

@Transactional

Significance
Ensures database operations run in a transaction.

Example

@Transactional
public void saveUser(User user) {
}

Summary of Most Important (Must Know for Interviews)

Top 12 you must remember:

@SpringBootApplication
@RestController
@Controller
@Service
@Repository
@Autowired
@GetMapping
@PostMapping
@RequestBody
@PathVariable
@Entity
@Transactional

These form the core of Spring Boot development.

