PART 2 — Charles Schwab’s revenue model (how Schwab makes money)

Charles Schwab is a financial services company providing:

brokerage accounts

wealth management

asset management

banking services.

Its revenue mainly comes from three big sources.

Net interest income (largest revenue source)

This is the biggest part of Schwab’s income.

When investors keep cash in their brokerage account, Schwab doesn’t leave that money idle. They move the cash to bank sweep accounts and invest it in safe securities like government bonds.

Schwab earns the difference between:

the interest they earn on investments

the interest they pay to customers.

This is called net interest income and accounts for a large portion of Schwab’s revenue.

Example

Investor cash in Schwab account = $1000
Schwab invests it and earns 4% interest
Schwab gives customer 1%

Schwab profit = 3%

With trillions of dollars of client assets, this becomes huge revenue.

Asset management and advisory fees

Schwab manages investment funds and portfolios.

They charge fees for:

mutual funds

ETFs

portfolio management

robo-advisors

financial advisors.

These fees are usually based on the total assets managed (for example 0.25%–1% annually).

Example

If a client has $100,000 managed by Schwab and the fee is 0.5%

Schwab earns $500 per year.

When millions of customers invest, this becomes billions.

Trading revenue

Even though many brokers advertise “zero commission trading”, Schwab still earns money from trading activity through:

options trading fees

margin lending (loans for trading)

payment for order flow

market making partnerships

securities lending.

In recent financial reports, Schwab generated hundreds of millions from trading activity due to high market participation.

Banking services

Schwab also runs a bank.

It makes money from:

mortgages

margin loans

credit products

deposits and lending spreads.

ETF and investment product fees

Schwab has its own ETFs and funds.

When investors buy them, Schwab earns management fees through its asset management division.

Simple summary

Schwab’s business model works like this:

Customers deposit money → invest through Schwab platform → Schwab earns money through interest, asset fees, and trading services.

Meanwhile companies like Mphasis build and maintain the technology systems that power those platforms.

